│ stop({"edit_points": [[444, 445,                                            │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/LoopUnrollAndJamPass.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.    │
│ Understanding the Issue: The crash occurs when trying to access subloops of │
│ a loop that has been invalidated. The assertion failure in                  │
│ GenericLoopInfo.h indicates that a loop object is being accessed after it   │
│ has been marked as invalid, which typically happens when the loop structure │
│ has been modified (e.g., through unrolling) but references to the old loop  │
│ structure are still being used.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log: The log shows  │
│ that the middle loop (%do.body2) is completely unrolled and jammed with     │
│ trip count 1. After this transformation, the loop structure changes - the   │
│ unrolled loop is removed from the loop hierarchy. However, the LoopNest     │
│ object still contains references to the original loops, including the       │
│ now-deleted loop.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis: In the tryToUnrollAndJamLoop   │
│ function, after a loop is fully unrolled (Result ==                         │
│ LoopUnrollResult::FullyUnrolled), the code calls U.markLoopAsDeleted(*L,    │
│ LoopName) only for the outermost loop (line 444-445). However, when an      │
│ inner loop is fully unrolled, it should also be marked as deleted to        │
│ prevent subsequent accesses to its invalidated state. The issue is that the │
│ current code only marks the outermost loop as deleted, but inner loops that │
│ get fully unrolled are not marked as deleted, leading to the assertion      │
│ failure when their subloops are accessed later.\n\n4. Proposed Edit         │
│ Point(s): The fix is to mark any loop as deleted when it is fully unrolled, │
│ not just the outermost loop. This ensures that all fully unrolled loops are │
│ properly invalidated in the LPMUpdater, preventing subsequent accesses to   │
│ their invalidated state.\n\n5. Conclusion: By marking all fully unrolled    │
│ loops as deleted (not just the outermost one), we ensure that the loop      │
│ analysis infrastructure properly tracks which loops are no longer valid,    │
│ preventing the assertion failure when accessing subloops of invalidated     │
│ loops."})                                                                   │
